Here are some references from another application to consider:

1. The Service Layer (Communicating with Gemini)
This is the core wrapper. It uses the @google/genai SDK. Note how it accepts the API Key and Model ID dynamically in the constructor.

"import { GoogleGenAI } from "@google/genai";

export class GeminiService {
  private ai: GoogleGenAI;
  private modelId: string;

  // 1. Accept the User's API Key and selected Model here
  constructor(apiKey: string, modelId: string = 'gemini-2.5-flash') {
    this.ai = new GoogleGenAI({ apiKey }); 
    this.modelId = modelId;
  }

  // 2. The function to call the API
  async generateContent(prompt: string, isJson: boolean = false): Promise<string> {
    try {
      const response = await this.ai.models.generateContent({
        model: this.modelId,
        contents: [
            {
                role: 'user',
                parts: [{ text: prompt }]
            }
        ],
        // 3. Optional: Enforce JSON output if your app needs structured data
        config: isJson ? { responseMimeType: "application/json" } : undefined
      });

      return response.text || '';
    } catch (error) {
      console.error("Gemini API Error:", error);
      throw error;
    }
  }
}"

2. The UI Layer (Handling User Input & State)
This shows how to manage the API key input, model selection, and instantiation of the service within a React component.

"import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import { GeminiService } from '../services/geminiService';

const MyComponent = () => {
  // 1. State for API Key (often loaded from localStorage for convenience)
  const [apiKey, setApiKey] = useState(localStorage.getItem('geminiKey') || '');

  // 2. State for Model Selection
  const [model, setModel] = useState('gemini-2.5-flash');

  // 3. Save key to local storage when it changes (optional UX improvement)
  useEffect(() => localStorage.setItem('geminiKey', apiKey), [apiKey]);

  const handleStartAnalysis = async () => {
    if (!apiKey) { alert('API Key required'); return; }

    // 4. Create a new instance with the CURRENT key and model
    const gemini = new GeminiService(apiKey, model);

    try {
        const result = await gemini.generateContent("Analyze this text...");
        console.log(result);
    } catch (e) {
        alert("Error calling Gemini");
    }
  };

  return (
    <div>
      {/* API Key Input */}
      <input 
        type="password" 
        value={apiKey} 
        onChange={e => setApiKey(e.target.value)} 
        placeholder="Enter Gemini API Key"
      />

      {/* Model Selector */}
      <select value={model} onChange={e => setModel(e.target.value)}>
        <option value="gemini-2.5-flash">Gemini 2.5 Flash (Fast)</option>
        <option value="gemini-2.5-pro">Gemini 2.5 Pro (Smarter)</option>
      </select>

      <button onClick={handleStartAnalysis}>Start</button>
    </div>
  );
};"

3. Model Constants (Defining Available Models)
It is best practice to keep a configuration file of available models and their specific attributes (like Rate Limits / RPM) so you can easily update them later.

"export const TA_MODEL_INFO: Record<string, { name: string; rpm: number }> = {
    'gemini-2.5-pro': { name: 'Gemini 2.5 Pro', rpm: 2 },
    'gemini-2.5-flash': { name: 'Gemini 2.5 Flash', rpm: 10 },
    'gemini-2.5-flash-lite': { name: 'Gemini 2.5 Flash Lite', rpm: 15 },
    // You can add 'gemini-1.5-pro' etc here if needed
};"

Key Takeaways :
Do not hardcode keys: Always allow the user to input process.env.API_KEY (if server-side) or a text input (if client-side like this app).
Instantiate on demand: Create new GeminiService(key, model) inside your execution function, not at the top level of the file. This ensures it always uses the latest key/model the user selected.
Use responseMimeType: "application/json": If you are building an app that needs to display data in charts or tables (like this Analyzer), strictly enforcing JSON mode in the API call is crucial for reliability.

